<paragraph blockId="6.[264,1325,1381,1647]" pageId="6" pageNumber="43">
Newly recorded in Nova 
<collectingCountry box="[606,679,1461,1487]" name="United Kingdom" pageId="6" pageNumber="43">Scotia</collectingCountry>
(
<figureCitation box="[695,768,1461,1487]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="7.[264,368,1219,1243]" captionTargetBox="[444,1140,639,1206]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[440,1147,634,1207]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 4. Distribution of Dendroides canadensis and Schizotus cervicalis in the Maritime Provinces of Canada." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/173000/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="43">
Fig. 
<number box="[750,768,1461,1487]" pageId="6" pageNumber="43" value="4.0">4</number>
</figureCitation>
). In 
<collectingCountry box="[820,908,1461,1487]" name="Canada" pageId="6" pageNumber="43">Canada</collectingCountry>
recorded from Ontario and Québec (
<bibRefCitation author="Campbell" box="[272,472,1501,1527]" pageId="6" pageNumber="49" refString="Campbell, J. M. (1991 d) Family Pyrochroidae: fire-coloured beetles. In: Bousquet, Y. (Ed.). Checklist of the Beetles of Canada and Alaska. Agriculture Canada Publication 1861 / E. pp. 269." type="journal article" year="1991" yearSuffix="d">
Campbell 
<number box="[395,457,1501,1527]" pageId="6" pageNumber="43" value="1991.0">1991</number>
d
</bibRefCitation>
); broadly distributed in the eastern and central 
<collectingCountry box="[1020,1176,1501,1527]" name="United States of America" pageId="6" pageNumber="43">United States</collectingCountry>
from Maine to 
<collectingCountry box="[298,395,1541,1567]" name="Georgia" pageId="6" pageNumber="43">Georgia</collectingCountry>
, west to Nebraska, Kansas, and Texas (
<bibRefCitation author="Downie" box="[883,1172,1541,1567]" pageId="6" pageNumber="50" refString="Downie, N. M. &amp; Arnett, R. H., Jr. (1996) The beetles of northeastern North America. Sandhill Crane Press, Gainesville, Florida. 1721 pp." type="book" year="1996">
Downie &amp; Arnett 
<number box="[1109,1172,1541,1567]" pageId="6" pageNumber="43" value="1996.0">1996</number>
</bibRefCitation>
). Larvae are found beneath bark and in decomposing wood within standing dead deciduous and coniferous logs, particularly in riparian areas; adults are nocturnal (
<bibRefCitation author="Young" box="[1051,1201,1621,1647]" pageId="6" pageNumber="51" refString="Young, D. A. (2002) Pyrochroidae Latreille 1807. In: Arnett, R. H., Jr., Thomas, M. C., Skelley, P. E. &amp; Frank, J. H. (Eds.). American Beetles, Volume 2: Polyphaga: Scarabaeoidea through Curculionoidea. CRC Press, Boca Raton, USA. pp. 540 - 543." type="journal article" year="2002">
Young 
<number box="[1137,1201,1621,1647]" pageId="6" pageNumber="43" value="2002.0">2002</number>
</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
